It's a small part of the market.

00:51:03.970 --> 00:51:08.130
As a result, if I'm a virus writer,
I'm not going to go after that.

00:51:08.180 --> 00:51:11.410
I'm going to go to the big stage,
which is the 95% of computers

00:51:11.410 --> 00:51:13.420
out there that are Windows,
right?

00:51:13.500 --> 00:51:15.450
You hear that a lot.

00:51:15.610 --> 00:51:19.020
To that I say, hey,
we'll run that experiment.

00:51:23.150 --> 00:51:28.540
We'll take the 25% market share and
we'll see if we're secure or not.

00:51:28.590 --> 00:51:30.100
Maybe we'll be, maybe we won't.

00:51:30.100 --> 00:51:32.060
But we'll run that exercise.

00:51:32.110 --> 00:51:35.980
The point is, at the end of the day,
it doesn't really matter why.

00:51:36.310 --> 00:51:41.920
We have not yet had, knock on wood,
nobody's perfect.

00:51:41.920 --> 00:51:44.410
We haven't had a major virus yet.

00:51:44.900 --> 00:52:15.600
[Transcript missing]

00:52:16.870 --> 00:52:20.230
The best way to stomp out bugs
is to have somebody do peer

00:52:20.230 --> 00:52:22.260
review and look at your work.

00:52:22.260 --> 00:52:23.930
Have some other eyes look at it.

00:52:24.190 --> 00:52:26.630
You guys have all done,
you either develop code or

00:52:26.690 --> 00:52:30.120
done engineering projects,
and you see things from one angle.

00:52:30.120 --> 00:52:33.200
Somebody else comes along and
they'll look at it from a very

00:52:33.200 --> 00:52:35.420
different angle and find an error.

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:37.550
Well,
that's what open source is all about,

00:52:37.600 --> 00:52:40.320
is peer review,
having other people look at the code.

00:52:40.320 --> 00:52:43.780
And that's something we think
has really been effective for us.

00:52:43.800 --> 00:52:45.000
We get ahead of it.

00:52:45.020 --> 00:52:48.510
Matter of fact,
we find that a majority of people warning

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:53.790
us about a potential flaw comes from
outside of our development organization.

00:52:53.790 --> 00:52:55.800
It's someone else
looking at it and saying,

00:52:55.800 --> 00:52:56.760
"Oh, look at that.

00:52:56.860 --> 00:52:58.800
That could be a problem."
These are theoretical,

00:52:58.800 --> 00:53:00.800
but we get to fix them ahead of time.

00:53:00.800 --> 00:53:02.730
So we have a lot of eyes looking at that.

00:53:02.800 --> 00:53:07.160
Contrast with a proprietary approach
where you have to trust the vendor

00:53:07.160 --> 00:53:11.650
and that particular development
organization to get every single bug.

00:53:11.800 --> 00:53:12.790
You just have to trust the vendor.

00:53:13.800 --> 00:53:15.800
You just have to trust
that they're doing it.

00:53:15.800 --> 00:53:21.800
And you also know that there's no outside
kind of auditing going on of their code.

00:53:21.800 --> 00:53:23.760
It's only that one organization.

00:53:23.780 --> 00:53:28.510
And you tend to get a pretty single
view of the world from that standpoint.

00:53:28.920 --> 00:53:30.800
So we think that's been really good.

00:53:30.880 --> 00:53:34.150
The other interesting thing
is we also built Mac OS X from

00:53:34.220 --> 00:53:35.800
the ground up to be secure.

00:53:35.820 --> 00:53:36.800
And that's also paid dividends.

00:53:36.800 --> 00:53:40.250
You know, a lot of ways,
we had the advantage because

00:53:40.250 --> 00:53:42.800
Mac OS X is a new operating system.

00:53:42.800 --> 00:53:47.030
We can develop that after we knew about
the whole internet and we knew about a

00:53:47.030 --> 00:53:49.740
lot of the potential flaws out there.

00:53:49.940 --> 00:53:53.800
So we could build it in as we
built Mac OS X from the ground up.

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:56.010
So as a result,
when you look at the things we

00:53:56.090 --> 00:53:59.750
